The Abuja Division of the Federal High Court, on Monday, struck out a suit that accused Governor Godwin Obaseki of Edo state of engaging in certificate forgery. Justice Anwuli Chikere terminated hearing on the matter after the plaintiffs failed to appear in court when the suit was called up for mention. Those listed as Plaintiffs in the suit marked FHC/ABJ/CS/553/2020 are Edobor Williams, Ugbesia Abudu Godwin, and Amedu Dauda Anakhu. They had alleged forgery case was that the Edo State Governor, Obaseki, who is seeking to be re-elected, forged the Bachelor of Arts (B.A.) certificate in Classical Studies he claimed to have obtained from the University of Ibadan. The plaintiffs told the court that the alleged certificate forgery was in contravention of section 182(1)(i) of the Constitution of the Federal Republic of Nigeria 1999, as amended. Consequently, they urged the court to among others, declare that the defendant (Obaseki) is not qualified to run or seek election to the office of the governor of Edo State. Meanwhile, when the case was mentioned on Monday, neither the plaintiffs nor their lawyers were present in court. Governor Obaseki was also not represented by any lawyer. In a bench ruling, Justice Chikere struck out the case. Vanguard News Nigeria. An Abuja High Court sitting in Apo, Gudu District, on Friday, dismissed a certificate forgery suit filed by one Uchenna Nnadi against Sen. Andy Uba. June 30, 2017 In "News" An Abuja High Court sitting in Apo, Gudu District, on Friday, dismissed a certificate forgery suit filed by one Uchenna Nnadi against Sen. Andy Uba. June 30, 2017 In "News" The national leadership of APC yesterday set up a committee to screen its six governorship aspirants in Edo State, saying without prejudice to the work of the committee and that of the Screening Appeals Panel, the National Working Committee, NWC, has the final say on the fate of the aspirants. June 10, 2020 In "News"